[Guest]: me minimum yeah uh but uh okay so let's get on with our topic of the show and it's also relevant

00:10:11.840 --> 00:10:17.760
[Guest]: for us to have this conversation on the eve of the national elections in india amit you've been

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:23.840
[Guest]: talking about public choice and public choice theory for quite some time and how it can shed

00:10:23.840 --> 00:10:30.400
[Guest]: new light on you know why things are the way they are when it comes to the government in india and

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:35.360
[Guest]: with other things so tell me a little about what public choice is all about so public choice is

00:10:35.360 --> 00:10:40.160
[Amit Varma]: really my favorite branch of economics and i keep saying that it's see economics to me you know

00:10:40.160 --> 00:10:44.480
[Amit Varma]: it's not some arcane subject economics is the subject of human behavior under conditions of

00:10:44.480 --> 00:10:50.160
[Amit Varma]: scarcity but basically it's the study of human behavior and public choice is a branch of that

00:10:50.160 --> 00:10:54.640
[Amit Varma]: which has incredible insights for the state of india today if you want to understand the indian

00:10:54.640 --> 00:10:59.280
[Amit Varma]: state the indian government why are people corrupt why do politicians behave the way they do

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:04.000
[Amit Varma]: all of those things and it helps in the central insight of public choice theory is this that

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:08.320
[Amit Varma]: people in government whether they're politicians or bureaucrats are human beings who respond to

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:13.200
[Amit Varma]: incentives so you know economists speak in terms of incentives and they're like okay

00:11:13.200 --> 00:11:17.120
[Amit Varma]: this is how within this market different parties behave these are the incentives they have

00:11:18.160 --> 00:11:23.520
[Amit Varma]: and you must also think of government like that and when you look at government action

00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:28.000
[Amit Varma]: everything becomes explicable if you look at it through the lens of interest now i write a

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.400
[Amit Varma]: monthly column for lumber quint which is called politics without romance which is a phrase by

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:37.280
[Amit Varma]: james buchanan the father of public choice theory in a sense because politics without romance is

00:11:37.280 --> 00:11:40.960
[Amit Varma]: what public choice theory is you look at politics without romance you look at the incentives of

00:11:40.960 --> 00:11:47.520
[Amit Varma]: people you know how people really are and the first column of those in fact examined the question

00:11:47.520 --> 00:11:52.960
[Amit Varma]: that people often ask a lot that you know back in the days of independence we had so many great

00:11:52.960 --> 00:11:57.840
[Amit Varma]: leaders uh you know but today you look at all the politicians they're all venal corrupt guys

00:11:57.840 --> 00:12:03.040
[Amit Varma]: why and people bemoan it as if you know we had good people then we have bad people now lots of

00:12:03.040 --> 00:12:09.040
[Amit Varma]: nostalgia gone are the great days of you know stalwart leaders who could whether it's nehru or

00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:14.000
[Amit Varma]: patel or whoever your favorite hero of choices but my point is that it's not that we had great

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:18.160
[Amit Varma]: leaders then and we had great leaders now we had great incentives and and the incentives that we

00:12:18.160 --> 00:12:23.360
[Amit Varma]: have now are guaranteed to produce us venal crooks and the reason for that for example is that

00:12:23.360 --> 00:12:29.440
[Amit Varma]: what animated the people who fought for india's freedom uh they had no chance of getting to

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:34.240
[Amit Varma]: government they had no chance of getting to power and making money from it so those sort of baser

00:12:34.240 --> 00:12:39.040
[Amit Varma]: instincts were not there people who wanted to make money or have power over others did other

00:12:39.040 --> 00:12:44.240
[Amit Varma]: things they did not fight for india's freedom because the the the risk reward ratio was way

00:12:44.240 --> 00:12:49.040
[Amit Varma]: out of whack so all of these people were high-minded people who were driven by principles

00:12:49.040 --> 00:12:53.360
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth and therefore you have all these great leaders and if you look at that

00:12:53.360 --> 00:12:57.760
[Amit Varma]: generation of leaders in the 30s and 40s and so on the nehru's and patel's and even the shama

00:12:57.760 --> 00:13:01.520
[Amit Varma]: prashad mukherjee's and so on it doesn't matter which side of the spectrum you are they are

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:06.000
[Amit Varma]: animated by higher principles whether or not you specifically agree with those principles

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:10.160
[Amit Varma]: what we have today is that you're animated by different things the state is such a bloated

00:13:10.160 --> 00:13:14.640
[Amit Varma]: beast and there is so much power that typically what are the incentives for a politician the

00:13:14.640 --> 00:13:20.000
[Amit Varma]: incentives for a politician is i want to win the next election and come to power so he needs two

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:24.640
[Amit Varma]: things for this one is he needs money because elections in india are incredibly costly the

00:13:24.640 --> 00:13:29.360
[Amit Varma]: money comes to him from special interest groups and that means that they want a quid pro quo of

00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:34.640
[Amit Varma]: some sort so it could be for example an association of small retailers who pays you money and in

00:13:34.640 --> 00:13:39.600
[Amit Varma]: return for their funding you you have to look after their interest maybe by banning fdi and

00:13:39.600 --> 00:13:45.600
[Amit Varma]: retail so and this is a very concrete example because bjp until recently used to be against fdi

00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:50.880
[Amit Varma]: in retail because they were a party funded by small retailers and the aam aadmi party in delhi

00:13:50.880 --> 00:13:55.840
[Amit Varma]: still is against fdi in retail and you have any kind of interventions in markets like that

00:13:55.840 --> 00:14:00.160
[Amit Varma]: typically what they're doing is they're harming the consumer at large to the benefit of the small

00:14:00.160 --> 00:14:03.440
[Amit Varma]: interest group in this case you're harming all the consumers who would benefit from a more

00:14:03.440 --> 00:14:08.960
[Amit Varma]: competitive retail market and they're benefiting the small retailers in question and so people say

00:14:08.960 --> 00:14:13.600
[Amit Varma]: for example arvind kejriwal isn't corrupt but hey you know what is this corruption is an inbuilt

00:14:13.600 --> 00:14:18.240
[Amit Varma]: part of the political the electoral system but anyway i don't want to you know we shouldn't name

00:14:18.240 --> 00:14:22.480
[Amit Varma]: specific politicians here so the point is that this is one of the incentives of politicians

00:14:22.480 --> 00:14:27.920
[Amit Varma]: today are driven by the interest groups that play on whose money they are dependent so it is not just

00:14:27.920 --> 00:14:32.320
[Amit Varma]: that you know prime minister modi people say is captured by ambani adani it's like come on i mean

00:14:32.320 --> 00:14:37.040
[Amit Varma]: every government was ever was captured by ambani you basically have you know different kinds of

00:14:37.040 --> 00:14:42.560
[Amit Varma]: interest groups running the show and the second kind of pressure group is voters because india's

00:14:42.560 --> 00:14:47.840
[Amit Varma]: politics is all identity politics it's the first pass of votes vote system it's a very fractured

00:14:47.840 --> 00:14:53.360
[Amit Varma]: electorate and therefore every election typically goes down to figuring out which are your vote

00:14:53.360 --> 00:14:57.600
[Amit Varma]: banks will this caste support me will that particular class of people support me what is

00:14:57.600 --> 00:15:03.760
[Amit Varma]: your vote bank and then catering to that vote bank and using patronage to benefit that vote bank in

00:15:03.760 --> 00:15:10.400
[Amit Varma]: some way so that you get their votes so therefore all politicians are caught up in this endless

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:16.160
[Amit Varma]: cycle between power and money where then necessarily have to play these kind of games

00:15:16.160 --> 00:15:20.960
[Amit Varma]: and sell themselves out completely to get to power which then ensures that the only kinds of

00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:26.400
[Amit Varma]: people that politics attracts are people like that people who don't mind their principles being

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:31.120
[Amit Varma]: corroded and all of that who don't really care about the public service because where's the

00:15:31.120 --> 00:15:35.600
[Amit Varma]: incentive now those kind of people you won't see in politics anymore it's people like this

00:15:35.600 --> 00:15:41.120
[Guest]: so in a sense when we're talking about public choice then basically you're saying that people

00:15:41.840 --> 00:15:47.360
[Guest]: in power or government itself and those who are taking decisions are also governed by the same

00:15:47.360 --> 00:15:53.920
[Guest]: kind of economic logic that governs markets and so on so in that sense a politician here is a

00:15:53.920 --> 00:15:58.720
[Guest]: rational maximizer right of some sort where they're sort of maximizing their interest which

00:15:58.720 --> 00:16:05.840
[Guest]: is how do if i'm in power how do i stay in power and how do i get re-elected and so so in this

00:16:05.840 --> 00:16:12.240
[Guest]: context i want to ask about this voting process right so you talked about identity politics a

00:16:12.240 --> 00:16:23.680
[Guest]: little but so we as voters if we are notionally rational people why should we vote especially

00:16:23.680 --> 00:16:29.920
[Guest]: when there are corrupt politicians with other interests on the other side that's a rational

00:16:29.920 --> 00:16:35.360
[Amit Varma]: question and that leads to let me first answer questions of why we should not vote and then i'll

00:16:35.360 --> 00:16:39.520
[Amit Varma]: come to why we should vote and i'll have more reasons of the former kind but i think we should

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:45.920
[Amit Varma]: look at both sides of the case there are three reasons why we should not bother about voting

