[Amit Varma]: well-oiled system of government surely they will do the right thing but again you have to consider

00:33:18.640 --> 00:33:25.040
[Amit Varma]: their incentives and nothing uh you know sort of sums it up better than what is famously known as

00:33:25.040 --> 00:33:29.680
[Amit Varma]: parkinson's law which was framed in this book called parkinson's law by c north court parkinson

00:33:29.680 --> 00:33:35.680
[Amit Varma]: and if i may quote from that uh parkinson's law says quote work expands so as to fill the time

00:33:35.680 --> 00:33:40.080
[Amit Varma]: available for its completion stop code which i think all of us know whenever we have to do

00:33:40.080 --> 00:33:46.720
[Amit Varma]: something and uh two of the necessary uh corollaries of this are court an official

00:33:46.720 --> 00:33:53.360
[Amit Varma]: wants to multiply subordinates not rivals stop code and court officials make work for each other

00:33:53.360 --> 00:33:59.680
[Amit Varma]: stop code and what it kind of tells you is that the natural tendency for any bureaucrat is to want

00:33:59.680 --> 00:34:05.520
[Amit Varma]: to increase his power to have a bigger department to have bigger budgets to be more influential

00:34:05.520 --> 00:34:11.440
[Amit Varma]: and and to feel more relevant to justify their position more so in fact there's a um a famous

00:34:11.440 --> 00:34:16.240
[Amit Varma]: author called william in his canon who's who's written pioneering books on this in the late 60s

00:34:16.240 --> 00:34:21.680
[Amit Varma]: and 70s and so on including a famous book called bureaucracy and public economics so he says that

00:34:21.680 --> 00:34:28.400
[Amit Varma]: bureaucrats are motivated by quote salary perks of the office public reputation power patronage

00:34:28.400 --> 00:34:35.920
[Amit Varma]: and the ease of managing the bureau stop code and the result of this is that every bureaucrat

00:34:35.920 --> 00:34:40.240
[Amit Varma]: will attempt to expand his power and you will simply never have an occasion when a bureaucrat

00:34:40.240 --> 00:34:44.480
[Amit Varma]: is giving up any power let me tell you a great story of this have you ever heard of this government

00:34:44.480 --> 00:34:49.360
[Amit Varma]: department that used to exist in tamil nadu called cca i've heard of it but let me tell

00:34:49.360 --> 00:34:54.320
[Amit Varma]: you the story because it's a great story and i love telling it so in about 1984 and i think

00:34:54.320 --> 00:34:59.520
[Amit Varma]: vivek debroy first told the story in an old book of his so credit where that is due in 1984

00:35:00.080 --> 00:35:06.560
[Amit Varma]: the central government got an application from a government department of the in the government

00:35:06.560 --> 00:35:12.400
[Amit Varma]: of tamil nadu as far as i recall and the department was called cca and the department was applying for

00:35:12.400 --> 00:35:17.760
[Amit Varma]: higher budgets right so he decided let me look into what is the cca and what do they need higher

00:35:17.760 --> 00:35:24.480
[Amit Varma]: budgets for so he looked into it and uh his investigation his forensic investigation into

00:35:24.480 --> 00:35:30.640
[Amit Varma]: the origins of cca took him back to world war ii now so what happened there was when world war ii

00:35:30.640 --> 00:35:36.720
[Amit Varma]: was on winston churchill who used to smoke cigars used to get his cigars from cuba so the supply

00:35:36.720 --> 00:35:43.200
[Amit Varma]: lines from cuba dried up so instead what he decided to do is the second best cigars in the

00:35:43.200 --> 00:35:49.280
[Amit Varma]: world apparently were in a factory somewhere near what was then madras right so i think that

00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:53.760
[Amit Varma]: the trichinopoly cigars wherever i don't know where they're from but it was somewhere in tamil

00:35:53.760 --> 00:36:00.800
[Amit Varma]: nadu you had good cigars happening so churchill started getting his cigars from this place in

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:05.120
[Amit Varma]: tamil nadu and the imperial office and at that time of course india was part of the british

00:36:05.120 --> 00:36:09.120
[Amit Varma]: empire so a department was set up which would get him those cigars and the department was called

00:36:09.120 --> 00:36:15.600
[Amit Varma]: cca churchill cigar assistant right so cca stands for churchill cigar assistant the department was

00:36:15.600 --> 00:36:20.480
[Amit Varma]: set up at the time of the second world war to send cigars to churchill world war ii has ended

00:36:20.480 --> 00:36:25.440
[Amit Varma]: supply lines between cuba and england are open winston churchill is out of power winston churchill

00:36:25.440 --> 00:36:32.000
[Amit Varma]: has died okay india has become independent and we've come all the way to 1984 and that department

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:36.320
[Amit Varma]: called the churchill cigar assistant is still running still has a budget still has a

00:36:36.320 --> 00:36:42.320
[Amit Varma]: under secretary or whatever who has the gall to apply for a raise right a raise in the budget

00:36:42.320 --> 00:36:48.720
[Amit Varma]: and what this kind of illustrates is that once you add a little bit of responsibility or power

00:36:48.720 --> 00:36:55.040
[Amit Varma]: to government no one's given it up bro it's like uh so government never gets smaller it only gets

00:36:55.040 --> 00:36:59.360
[Amit Varma]: bigger and bigger in all these mad different directions and in this particular case of course

00:36:59.920 --> 00:37:04.960
[Amit Varma]: department was abolished when the central secretary or whatever just send what was

00:37:04.960 --> 00:37:09.360
[Amit Varma]: what i suppose would have been bureaucraties equivalent of wtf bro what are you doing

00:37:09.360 --> 00:37:15.440
[Amit Varma]: and so the department went off but this kind of illustrates or bureaucrats are always going to

00:37:15.440 --> 00:37:20.640
[Amit Varma]: add to their power as far as possible and this is a process which is quite separate from who the

00:37:20.640 --> 00:37:25.920
[Amit Varma]: politician in power may be or what his incentives may be politicians doing his own thing up on top

00:37:25.920 --> 00:37:30.800
[Amit Varma]: with state x checker bureaucrat meanwhile is quietly sitting expanding his power and

00:37:30.800 --> 00:37:36.320
[Amit Varma]: managing his risk to reward ratio and seeing that everything flows well so this budget

00:37:36.320 --> 00:37:41.680
[Guest]: maximization drive is something that i've come across many times and there are a few who have

00:37:41.680 --> 00:37:47.360
[Guest]: used it to their advantage so if you know that these are the interests of someone in power like

00:37:47.360 --> 00:37:57.600
[Guest]: for example um you know before the jnn urm started and the reason i like that national urban renewal

00:37:57.600 --> 00:38:01.520
[Guest]: mission scheme is simply because it was the first time sort of the government of india woke up and

00:38:01.520 --> 00:38:06.800
[Guest]: said hey cities are important to us not so much about what happened with the scheme and that

00:38:06.800 --> 00:38:12.560
[Guest]: happened because the urban development ministry was almost like a punishment posting you know

00:38:12.560 --> 00:38:18.640
[Guest]: it's a small department you know rural development has always been gigantic so therefore the person

00:38:18.640 --> 00:38:24.880
[Guest]: in charge would not have a large budget to command but supposing india started this national mission

00:38:24.880 --> 00:38:31.840
[Guest]: on urban renewal then it is in the interest of that person in charge over there to bat for it

00:38:31.840 --> 00:38:37.760
[Guest]: because ultimately he or she also gets a much larger budget at their disposal so this seems

00:38:37.760 --> 00:38:44.560
[Guest]: to happen at all levels right so one is maximizing their budgets and then creating more work to meet

00:38:45.120 --> 00:38:50.720
[Amit Varma]: the budget yeah and this is why you know no matter what party comes into power saying minimum

00:38:50.720 --> 00:38:55.040
[Amit Varma]: government and maximum governance or whatever nonsense so i don't think prime minister modi

00:38:55.040 --> 00:39:00.800
[Amit Varma]: g even intended to carry out those promises of his but even had he intended the pushback would

00:39:00.800 --> 00:39:05.520
[Amit Varma]: have been enormous because the point is politicians are on a tangent of their own bureaucrats are in

00:39:05.520 --> 00:39:10.240
[Amit Varma]: a tangent of their own arguably bureaucrats are more powerful in a sense because they hold all

00:39:10.240 --> 00:39:14.880
[Amit Varma]: the levers of the state so supposing for example you have the ayush ministry which does homeopathy

00:39:14.880 --> 00:39:20.960
[Amit Varma]: and ayurveda and you know all of that stuff and you decide that no we need to abolish this

00:39:20.960 --> 00:39:25.280
[Amit Varma]: department it's a waste of taxpayers money we are inflicting violence on taxpayers for what not

00:39:25.280 --> 00:39:29.760
[Amit Varma]: for this but the point is politician gives the order it goes to bureaucrat he says yes sir

00:39:29.760 --> 00:39:34.400
[Amit Varma]: let's do it. I'll make a committee because there are 8000 people who work here how do we fire them

00:39:34.400 --> 00:39:38.800
[Amit Varma]: what do we do blah blah blah blah blah blah what are the procedures let's make a committee

00:39:38.800 --> 00:39:42.720
[Amit Varma]: committee will sit committee will come back after six months then there'll be this procedural

00:39:42.720 --> 00:39:47.680
[Amit Varma]: problem then the ministry of finance will get involved this ministry falana ministry dimkara

00:39:47.680 --> 00:39:52.080
[Amit Varma]: ministry and before you know it the politician is focused on the short-term imperative of winning

00:39:52.080 --> 00:39:57.440
[Amit Varma]: the next election which is giving farm loan waiver or whatever it is and these structural reforms

00:39:57.440 --> 00:40:01.440
[Amit Varma]: are forgotten and shit never happens and everything grows and even that committee you set up

00:40:01.440 --> 00:40:06.000
[Amit Varma]: in the first place becomes a permanent committee and that's the nature of the beast it's like it's

