[Guest]: the 80s pretty much talks about every one of these issues right i mean many times when we're

00:40:19.360 --> 00:40:24.880
[Guest]: talking about lots of things happening in indian politics we teach public policy courses as well

00:40:24.880 --> 00:40:30.080
[Guest]: honestly i think i can learn more from that show than most of the courses that i attend

00:40:30.080 --> 00:40:37.120
[Guest]: but what i found interesting was that even that show was created in the light of public choice

00:40:37.120 --> 00:40:43.360
[Amit Varma]: theory and ideas coming to the fore right you know yes minister is mind-blowing and why is it

00:40:43.360 --> 00:40:48.880
[Amit Varma]: that people love that show and find it so funny because like all great humor it has that ring of

00:40:48.880 --> 00:40:54.640
[Amit Varma]: truth that they see what is happening and they're like you know it's both real and it's funny like

00:40:54.640 --> 00:41:00.720
[Amit Varma]: for example another great book that you know captures the nature of the indian state and was

00:41:00.720 --> 00:41:05.600
[Amit Varma]: written in the late 1960s is raag darbari by shrilal shukla now i can guarantee you that

00:41:05.600 --> 00:41:10.640
[Amit Varma]: shrilal shukla ji never read james bookannon or william niskanen or any of these people god

00:41:10.640 --> 00:41:17.200
[Amit Varma]: interluck but he had the artist's eye for what is at the core of every situation and he captures

00:41:17.200 --> 00:41:23.040
[Amit Varma]: the absurdity of the indian state and the indian bureaucracy so beautifully that you know and

00:41:23.040 --> 00:41:28.640
[Amit Varma]: that's why that book is such a revered classic in india and it's just magnificent and you know

00:41:28.640 --> 00:41:34.320
[Amit Varma]: what is art supposed to do art is supposed to reveal the human condition which both yes minister

00:41:34.320 --> 00:41:39.920
[Amit Varma]: and raag darbari do but also the human condition can be revealed by the social sciences public

00:41:39.920 --> 00:41:45.920
[Amit Varma]: choice economics can also then in a forensic way explain why is it that people behave in these

00:41:45.920 --> 00:41:51.920
[Amit Varma]: absurd ways and explain why something like churchill cigar assistant exists till 1984 and

00:41:51.920 --> 00:41:58.000
[Guest]: why it is rational for that to be the case so i mean given so all of this so the bureaucrat then

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:05.280
[Guest]: so one work expands budgets expand there is also risk aversion because playing it safe means that

00:42:05.280 --> 00:42:10.800
[Guest]: you don't get into trouble taking a risk means maybe there's a reward but you know more if things

00:42:10.800 --> 00:42:16.960
[Guest]: go wrong then you're in more trouble and the reward can't be that you get to double your salary or

00:42:16.960 --> 00:42:23.040
[Guest]: your position or something right you're still in that same system with uh of slowly escalating

00:42:23.040 --> 00:42:28.960
[Guest]: ladder that goes upwards so given all of this can we also talk a little bit about how

00:42:30.640 --> 00:42:37.600
[Guest]: corruption can be broken down into different things by public choice theory yeah i think

00:42:37.600 --> 00:42:44.240
[Amit Varma]: you know the thing is corruption is india's great big problem but it is a symptom it is not a root

00:42:44.240 --> 00:42:49.680
[Amit Varma]: cause of any specific disease right and i think uh you know most indians all indians would agree

00:42:49.680 --> 00:42:55.680
[Amit Varma]: that corruption is a huge problem but i don't think there's enough of an adequate appreciation

00:42:55.680 --> 00:42:58.640
[Amit Varma]: of what causes corruption corruption is not caused by bad people

00:43:04.880 --> 00:43:09.040
[Amit Varma]: you put a good person there the good person won't take a bribe no that is not what causes

00:43:09.040 --> 00:43:15.840
[Amit Varma]: corruption is caused by power right you give one set of people power over another set of people

00:43:15.840 --> 00:43:20.800
[Amit Varma]: they will be corrupt because as lord acton said power corrupts absolute power corrupts absolutely

00:43:20.800 --> 00:43:27.920
[Amit Varma]: and i would sort of say something which seems extremist but i kind of believe in it i would

00:43:27.920 --> 00:43:33.040
[Amit Varma]: say power always corrupts it is in the nature of power to corrupt because your incentives change

00:43:33.040 --> 00:43:38.480
[Amit Varma]: completely now what the problem with the indian state is that i often say the indian state is

00:43:38.480 --> 00:43:42.960
[Amit Varma]: both too large and too weak it's too weak because it doesn't do the few things it ought

00:43:42.960 --> 00:43:47.680
[Amit Varma]: to do properly like maintain rule of law or whatever the few basic things reasonable people

00:43:47.680 --> 00:43:51.600
[Amit Varma]: can all agree on doesn't have enough manpower doesn't have straight capacity doesn't do them

00:43:51.600 --> 00:43:56.640
[Amit Varma]: properly it is too large because it has too much procedure it might have too few people in some

00:43:56.640 --> 00:44:02.160
[Amit Varma]: places it has too much procedure in some other places now what is that procedure that procedure

00:44:02.160 --> 00:44:07.520
[Amit Varma]: is for example if you are starting a business and you need 40 licenses and for each one somebody has

00:44:07.520 --> 00:44:15.600
[Amit Varma]: a power to end your dreams so you have to pay them right and you know like i did an episode on

00:44:15.600 --> 00:44:22.880
[Amit Varma]: restaurant regulations many months ago and one of the revelations in in that episode was that

00:44:22.880 --> 00:44:28.480
[Amit Varma]: restaurant regulations at least in karnataka they have these two conflicting regulations where

00:44:28.480 --> 00:44:34.160
[Amit Varma]: the excise people or rather the people who look after alcohol say that a restaurant should only

00:44:34.160 --> 00:44:39.840
[Amit Varma]: have one entrance so they can monitor the inflow and outflow of alcohol only one entrance that is

00:44:39.840 --> 00:44:44.560
[Amit Varma]: mandated the fire department mandates that for safety purposes you have to have more than one

00:44:44.560 --> 00:44:50.400
[Amit Varma]: entrance so you have multiple entrances now the point is you whatever you however many entrances

00:44:50.400 --> 00:44:54.800
[Amit Varma]: you do you are breaking the law if you have one entrance fire department will come after you if

00:44:54.800 --> 00:45:01.680
[Amit Varma]: you have two entrances the alcohol guys will come after you so you have to bribe one of them and

00:45:01.680 --> 00:45:04.720
[Amit Varma]: the truth of the matter is you don't have to bribe one of them you have to bribe two of them

00:45:04.720 --> 00:45:09.920
[Amit Varma]: and you have to bribe the other 30 authorities involved which can this enough on the margins is

00:45:09.920 --> 00:45:14.400
[Amit Varma]: enough to stop new businesses opening and to drive many existing businesses which would otherwise be

00:45:14.400 --> 00:45:19.440
[Amit Varma]: barely profitable out of business and all of this is because you're giving discretion to government

00:45:19.440 --> 00:45:26.880
[Amit Varma]: servants who have the power to use this and if you think about it you know a lot of what people

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:32.160
[Amit Varma]: who should be looking after the rule of law stopping violence investigating murders and

00:45:32.160 --> 00:45:38.240
[Amit Varma]: rapes a lot of that effort instead goes on into figuring out how can we make money on the side

00:45:38.240 --> 00:45:42.880
[Amit Varma]: because of all these bad laws like many years back i had written a column called the matunga

00:45:42.880 --> 00:45:49.040
[Amit Varma]: racket and what the matunga racket was at that time 377 was still on the cards which made

00:45:49.600 --> 00:45:55.600
[Amit Varma]: homosexual sex effectively illegal so what the matunga racket would do is that these cops would

00:45:55.600 --> 00:46:01.040
[Amit Varma]: go on these online forums no grinder in those days were in 2007-2008 they would go on these

00:46:01.040 --> 00:46:06.880
[Amit Varma]: online forums and they would pretend to be gay men looking for other gay men and they would call

00:46:06.880 --> 00:46:12.000
[Amit Varma]: so and so to a spot near matunga station and the poor chap would turn up expecting an exciting

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:17.840
[Amit Varma]: rendezvous and three cops would surround him and they would say okay we'll file 377 or we'll call

00:46:17.840 --> 00:46:22.400
[Amit Varma]: your home and tell your parents or whatever unless matlab ki atm jaate hain put the guy's card in

00:46:22.400 --> 00:46:27.040
[Amit Varma]: take out whatever they feel like so on and so forth so i i wrote about it and it was a very

00:46:27.040 --> 00:46:31.200
[Amit Varma]: common racket and now it can't take place why because the discretion in the context of that

00:46:31.200 --> 00:46:36.000
[Amit Varma]: law is gone that law is gone so you cannot anymore catch a gay man at a railway station

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:42.480
[Amit Varma]: and extort money from him like this and a lot of what these bad laws do a lot of what these bad

00:46:42.480 --> 00:46:48.400
[Amit Varma]: regulations do is they amount to extortion and the people who are supposed to protect your rights

00:46:48.400 --> 00:46:53.120
[Amit Varma]: instead become the people who are extorting money from you and so this has been a bit of

00:46:53.120 --> 00:46:58.960
[Amit Varma]: a tangent but my central point is that to end corruption the best way to do it is a is a

00:46:58.960 --> 00:47:04.320
[Amit Varma]: twofold thing one is you reduce the discretion of the government in areas where the government

00:47:04.320 --> 00:47:09.920
[Amit Varma]: has no business being like the government has no business being in your bedroom as ever with 377

00:47:09.920 --> 00:47:14.960
[Amit Varma]: you remove laws like that and the government has no business deciding which business should exist

00:47:14.960 --> 00:47:19.600
[Amit Varma]: and who has a license or doesn't have a license take it out of that you know have complete ease

00:47:19.600 --> 00:47:25.600
[Amit Varma]: of business remove all of that rent seeking that is one way and the other way is in areas where

00:47:25.600 --> 00:47:30.320
[Amit Varma]: government does have to have power because there has to be a rule of law in certain areas government

00:47:30.320 --> 00:47:35.840
[Amit Varma]: will have power in those areas you figure out ways and to change the incentives by making it

00:47:35.840 --> 00:47:43.360
[Amit Varma]: more accountable and the key to that is by having governance which is as local as possible like on

00:47:43.360 --> 00:47:47.520
[Amit Varma]: the scene and the unseen i had my guest shruti rajgopalan who's actually a much bigger expert

00:47:47.520 --> 00:47:53.040
[Amit Varma]: in public choice economics and i could ever claim to be i'm just an enthusiast and shruti

00:47:53.040 --> 00:47:57.440
[Amit Varma]: spoke about urban governance from the point of the mismatch over power and governance

00:47:57.440 --> 00:48:04.160
[Amit Varma]: that your local legislator who you have control over uh you have power over doesn't actually he

00:48:04.160 --> 00:48:08.640
[Amit Varma]: can't do anything for you and the people who can do something for you are the state legislatures

00:48:08.640 --> 00:48:13.360
[Amit Varma]: who depend on the rural vote they don't give a shit about you so if governance is as local as

00:48:13.360 --> 00:48:19.280
[Amit Varma]: possible if cities have strong empowered mayors village panchayats are empowered as they are to

00:48:19.280 --> 00:48:23.760
[Amit Varma]: some degree now and you fix all of those local governance problems then you make them more

00:48:23.760 --> 00:48:30.000
[Amit Varma]: accountable so dual solution reduce discretion where not required and where you need the presence

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:34.080
[Amit Varma]: of the state make it more accountable by making government more local and figuring out other ways

00:48:34.080 --> 00:48:40.960
[Guest]: for better incentives so in a way this is also bringing in many market principles into even

00:48:40.960 --> 00:48:46.880
[Guest]: governmental thinking and so one along with discretion while i mean local can be a lot

